In this package we illustrate the meaning of an interface with package access: we have a tester class, with a main method that is able to create an object of the public class ImplementingClass, which implements the interface PackageAccessInterface, both in the package com.andreamazzon.session5.packageaccessinterfaces.

com.andreamazzon.session5.inheritinginterfaces - package com.andreamazzon.session5.inheritinginterfaces
Scope of this package is to illustrate that, differently from what happens with classes, multiple inheritance is possible for interfaces: an interface can indeed inherit from more than one interfaces.
com.andreamazzon.session5.interfaceexample - package com.andreamazzon.session5.interfaceexample
In this package we illustrate a first example of interface: and interface is a "completely abstract" class, as it only gives the returning type, name and arguments lists of the methods that a class "implementing" that interface must implement, and possibly static fields: it provides the "form" of a class implementing that interface, but not the implementation.
com.andreamazzon.session5.interfacesandpolymorphism.band - package com.andreamazzon.session5.interfacesandpolymorphism.band
In this package we show another example of polymorphism, connected with interfaces.
com.andreamazzon.session5.multipleinterfaceimplementation.animals - package com.andreamazzon.session5.multipleinterfaceimplementation.animals
Here we show how multiple implementation is possible with interfaces: the class Duck implements both the interfaces AnimalThatFlies (that has a method fly()) and AnimalThatSwims (that has a method swim()).
com.andreamazzon.session5.nameclasheswithinterfaces - package com.andreamazzon.session5.nameclasheswithinterfaces
This package illustrates possible problems due to name clashes when a class implements two interfaces which have two methods with the same name, same argument list but different return types.
com.andreamazzon.session5.nomultipleinheritance - package com.andreamazzon.session5.nomultipleinheritance
In this package we show why multiple inheritance is not allowed in Java: if a class inherits from two base classes, it can happen that the two classes have a method with same name, same argument list and different implementation.
